## Introduction

This article provides instructions how to establish SSH connections to remote workloads running development environments such as Visual Studio Code and PyCharm and direct access to web-based IDEs and tools.

## Remote development using SSH

In this section, we provide examples of using remote development using SSH for different IDEs and tools.

### PyCharm

To submit a workload, your image must run an SSH server, for example [OpenSSH](https://www.ssh.com/ssh/sshd/){target=_blank}. For the purpose of this article, we have created an image named `http://gcr.io/run-ai-demo/pycharm-demo`. The image runs both Python and SSH. Instructions on creating the image can be found on the [Run:ai Github](https://github.com/run-ai/docs/tree/master/quickstart/python%2Bssh){target=_blank}. The image is configured to use the root user and password for SSH.

Run the following command to submit a workload running the image:

```
runai submit build-remote -i gcr.io/run-ai-demo/pycharm-demo --interactive
```

The workload starts an sshd server on port22.

The next step is to run a command, port-forward, for the connection to be redirected to the local machine (127.0.0.1) on port 2222:

```
runai port-forward remote-dev --port 2222:22
```

!!! Note
    It is possible to connect to the container using a remote IP address. However, this would be less convenient as you must maintain port numbers manually and change them when remove access using the development tool. As an example, run the following:

    ```
    runai submit build-remote -i gcr.io/run-ai-demo/pycharm-demo -g 1 --interactive --service-type=nodeport --port 30022:22
    ```

    * The Job starts an sshd server on port 22.
    * The Job redirects the external port 30022 to port 22 and uses a [Node Port](https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/services-networking/service/#publishing-services-service-types){target=_blank} service type.

    * Run:`runai list jobs`
    * Next to the Job, under the "Service URL" column you can find the IP address and port. The port is 30222

Follow these steps to access the remote container created by run:ai from JetBrain’s Charm.

Under PyCharm → Preferences go to Project → Python Interpreter

1.  Add a new SSH Interpreter
2.  As Host, use the IP address above and change the port to the above and use the username `root`
3.  You are prompted for a password. Enter `root`
4.  Apply the settings and run the code via this interpreter

You can see your project uploaded to the container and running remotely.

### Visual Studio Code

Follow these steps to access the remote container created by Run:ai, from Visual Studio Code:

1.  Under Visual Studio code install the Remote SSH extension
2.  Create an ssh entry to the service by editing .ssh/config file or use the command Remote-SSH: Connect to Host... from the Command Palette
3.  Enter the IP address and port from above (e.g. `ssh root@35.34.212.12 -p 30022` or `ssh root@127.0.0.1 -p 2222`).
4.  User and password are root Using VS Code, install the Python extension on the remote machine Write your first python code and run it remotely.

### X11 & PyCharm

**X11** is a window system for the UNIX operating systems. **X11 forwarding** allows executing a program remotely through an SSH connection. Meaning, the executable file itself is hosted on a different machine than where the graphical interface is being displayed. The graphical windows are forwarded to your local machine through the SSH connection.

This articles explains how to set-up X11 forwarding from a Run:ai-based container to a [PyCharm](https://www.jetbrains.com/pycharm/){target=_blank} IDE on a remote machine.

#### Submitting a workload

You must run an SSH server (e.g [OpenSSH](https://www.ssh.com/ssh/sshd/){target=_blank}). For the purposes of this article, we have created an image named `gcr.io/run-ai-demo/quickstart-x-forwarding`. The image runs:

*   Python
*   SSH Daemon configured for X11Forwarding
*   OpenCV python library for image handling

See here for details on [creating the image](https://github.com/run-ai/docs/tree/master/quickstart/x-forwarding){target=_blank}. The image is configured to use the root user and password for SSH.

Run the following command to connect to the container as if it were running locally:

``` bash
runai submit xforward-remote -i gcr.io/run-ai-demo/quickstart-x-forwarding --interactive \
    --service-type=portforward --port 2222:22
```

The terminal displays the connection:

```bash
The job 'xforward-remote' has been submitted successfully
You can run `runai describe job xforward-remote -p team-a` to check the job status
INFO[0007] Waiting for job to start
Waiting for job to start
Waiting for job to start
Waiting for job to start
INFO[0045] Job started
Open access point(s) to service from localhost:2222
Forwarding from [::1]:2222 -> 22
```

* The workload starts an sshd server on port 22.
* The connection is redirected to the local machine (127.0.0.1) on port 2222

#### Setting-up the X11 forwarding tunnel

Connect to the new workload by running:

``` bash
ssh -X root@127.0.0.1 -p 2222
```

Note the -X flag.

Run:
```
echo $DISPLAY
```

Copy the value. It is used as a PyCharm environment variable.

!!! Important
    The ssh terminal should remain active throughout the session.

#### Setting-up PyCharm interpreter

1.  Under PyCharm | Preferences go to Project → Python Interpreter
2.  Add a new SSH Interpreter
3.  As Host, use `localhost`. Change the port to the above (`2222`) and use the username root
4.  You are prompted for a password. Enter `root`
5.  Make sure to set the correct path of the Python binary. In our case it's `/usr/local/bin/python`
6.  Apply your settings
7.  Under PyCharm configuration set the following environment variables:
    1.  __DISPLAY__ - Set environment variable you copied earlier
    2.  __HOME__ - In our case it's `/root`. This is required for the X11 authentication to work




## Direct access to web-based IDEs and tools

In this section, we provide examples of using direct access to web-based IDEs and tools.

### Jupyter Notebook

Follow these steps to access JupyterLab via a secured external URL.

![](data:image/png;base64,){ style="border: 2px solid #000; border-radius: 5px;" }

2.  Click **+NEW WORKLOAD**
3.  Select if the workload type is a workspace, training or inference

    ![](data:image/png;base64,){ style="border: 2px solid #000; border-radius: 5px;" }

    ![](data:image/png;base64,){ style="border: 2px solid #000; border-radius: 5px;" }

## Accessing JupyterLab via the CLI

You can access JupyterLab through a command-line interface (CLI) by deploying a continerized version using the jupyter/base-notebook image. Follow these steps to set-up and connect.

### Submitting the workload

Use the following command to submit a workload named `test-jupyter` in the `p1` project.

This command configures the container to expose port `8888`, which JupyterLab listens on.

```bash
runai submit test-jupyter -p p1 -i jupyter/base-notebook --service-type external-url --port 8888
```

![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAAEAAAABCAYAAAAfFcSJAAAADUlEQVR4XmP4//8LAwAI5gLzKCk9dQAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==){ style="border: 2px solid #000; border-radius: 5px;" }

### Checking the workload status

1.  To obtain the details of your workload and retrieve the service URL, run:
    ```
    runai describe job test-jupyter -p p1
    ```
2.  In the command output, look for “Service URLs” to find the URl that Run:ai generated for your JupyterLab session:  
    ![](data:image/png;base64,){ style="border: 2px solid #000; border-radius: 5px;" }
3.  Copy the Service URL from the command output and paste it into your web browser to connect you to your JupyterLab environment.

## Setting-up JupyterLab with Port forwarding

Follow these steps to use port forwarding to access JupyterLab running as a workload in your Kubernetes cluster from your own laptop.

1.  Submit the workload
2.  Deploy your JupyterLab environment without specifying an external URL or port.  
    Use the command:
    ``` bash
    runai submit test-jupyter -i jupyter/base-notebook -p p-1
    ```

3.  Set-up port forwarding to JupyterLab, which listens on port 8888 inside the cluster, to be accessible via port 31000 (or any other port) on your local machine.  
    Use the command:
    ``` bash
    runai port-forward test-jupyter -p p-1 --port 31000:8888
    ```
4.  Open a web browser and navigate to [http://localhost:31000](about:blank). The URL directs your browser to connect through the local port you mapped to the service running inside the cluster, allowing you to interact with JupyterLab as if it were running locally.
